1
00:00:14,875 --> 00:00:19,958
We will enter the prison now, and this here is the vehicle entrance

2
00:00:20,833 --> 00:00:21,833
Into the basement

3
00:00:22,916 --> 00:00:23,916
And the first step

4
00:00:26,166 --> 00:00:27,500
In the prison routine

5
00:00:29,500 --> 00:00:34,291
You go down and drive the vehicles into
the basement, and this was the car garage

6
00:00:34,791 --> 00:00:40,833
For the prisoners’ vehicles and
for the jailers’ and interrogators’ cars

7
00:00:41,875 --> 00:00:44,291
This entire area was a car garage

8
00:00:45,166 --> 00:00:46,458
Sometimes a person would go out

9
00:00:47,458 --> 00:00:52,500
They take him out of prison without a
blindfold, and he notices the prisoners’ cars

10
00:00:53,041 --> 00:00:54,291
Someone might recognize them

11
00:00:55,625 --> 00:00:58,833
This is the door of the investigation room and the group cells

12
00:00:59,291 --> 00:01:02,208
And this is the main prison gate

13
00:01:03,166 --> 00:01:07,500
We enter from here, and the first room
is the custody and investigation room

14
00:01:09,833 --> 00:01:13,875
We enter to the right, where the solitary cells and group cells are

15
00:01:14,625 --> 00:01:16,541
And on the left side, there is a kitchen belonging to them

16
00:01:17,250 --> 00:01:19,583
There is a hidden group cell

17
00:01:20,250 --> 00:01:22,166
And there is a regular group cell

18
00:01:23,500 --> 00:01:28,708
From here we enter the corridor
of the solitary cells and group cells

19
00:01:29,208 --> 00:01:31,916
Here comes the first group cell, then the second

20
00:01:32,916 --> 00:01:38,000
And here were the solitary cells. They have
cleaned the area and removed the partitions

21
00:01:38,125 --> 00:01:40,000
This room was divided into three solitary cells

22
00:01:40,458 --> 00:01:43,125
The first, second, and third solitary cells

23
00:01:43,625 --> 00:01:45,333
I visited all these solitary cells

24
00:01:45,833 --> 00:01:47,625
I was imprisoned in the second one

25
00:01:47,958 --> 00:01:50,625
On both my right and left sides, we
could communicate with each other

26
00:01:51,583 --> 00:01:56,500
Interviewer: Faraj, tell us about
the days you spent in that solitary cell

27
00:01:57,291 --> 00:02:01,000
When I first entered, they put me in the third solitary cell

28
00:02:01,541 --> 00:02:05,708
I stayed two days, then they moved me to another
group cell for about a month, then back to this one

29
00:02:06,083 --> 00:02:09,250
Here I lived the most tragic period of my imprisonment

30
00:02:09,625 --> 00:02:13,208
Because on both sides of me there were women

31
00:02:13,666 --> 00:02:18,125
We could hear the sounds of interrogation and torture

32
00:02:18,791 --> 00:02:23,791
And worse than that, the ventilation opening of the cell

33
00:02:24,250 --> 00:02:27,958
Overlooked the basement and the car garage

34
00:02:28,416 --> 00:02:30,666
So when a prisoner was taken for execution

35
00:02:31,208 --> 00:02:33,041
We knew he would be executed before he left

36
00:02:33,458 --> 00:02:38,791
Because they carried digging tools, and we
heard them through the ventilation opening

37
00:02:39,041 --> 00:02:44,791
They placed the prisoner opposite me in the corridor,
asked him some questions, then took him away

38
00:02:45,250 --> 00:02:49,208
They disappeared for two hours or
more and returned without the prisoner

39
00:02:50,666 --> 00:02:54,416
We used to communicate with each
other, as there was a bathroom at the back

40
00:02:55,708 --> 00:02:58,500
We communicated with those to the
right and left, we could hear each other

41
00:02:58,791 --> 00:03:04,750
After the women had left, they placed one of my
relatives, Huthaifa al-Haj Abd, who was killed

42
00:03:05,250 --> 00:03:09,708
And Faisal Saad Rajoub, a young man from Homs, was also killed

43
00:03:10,125 --> 00:03:14,666
We eventually gathered in one cell, the sixth solitary cell

44
00:03:15,416 --> 00:03:20,666
It was the most dangerous solitary cell in
the prison, as few people ever came out of it

45
00:03:21,458 --> 00:03:29,208
It was designated as a solitary cell without
a ventilation opening toward the garage

46
00:03:29,666 --> 00:03:32,458
It was a small room where they placed those sentenced to death

47
00:03:33,125 --> 00:03:35,416
So they had no chance to escape

48
00:03:35,875 --> 00:03:41,500
It was far from the investigation room;
we never knew who entered or left it

49
00:03:43,833 --> 00:03:48,125
In the other solitary cells, we could feel
when prisoners were brought in or taken out

50
00:03:48,583 --> 00:03:52,625
Here, we never knew what was happening outside

51
00:03:53,208 --> 00:03:55,833
Witness: We could only communicate a little
Interviewer: How many days did you stay here?

52
00:03:55,875 --> 00:03:57,416
I stayed here 15 days

53
00:03:58,583 --> 00:04:01,708
At first, they left me alone for about 10 days

54
00:04:02,333 --> 00:04:05,583
Then they brought the young man, Faisal Saad Rajoub

55
00:04:06,250 --> 00:04:11,916
We stayed five or six days together, and a little
further from our cell was another with two women

56
00:04:12,625 --> 00:04:13,625
They brought in...

57
00:04:15,791 --> 00:04:22,125
A well-known prisoner, so they changed everyone’s places

58
00:04:23,416 --> 00:04:25,083
The young man and I

59
00:04:25,750 --> 00:04:30,125
Were placed in the group cell, and
the women were moved to solitary cells

60
00:04:30,166 --> 00:04:32,791
They took one woman, and the other stayed two days before leaving

61
00:04:33,708 --> 00:04:38,000
After several days, they brought the male prisoner and placed him here

62
00:04:38,375 --> 00:04:42,125
I communicated with him through the bathroom; that’s how we talked

63
00:04:43,000 --> 00:04:45,791
He told me his name was Ahmad al-Hassan al-Ibrahim

64
00:04:46,500 --> 00:04:49,458
He was imprisoned for the second time because of his brother Musleh

65
00:04:49,500 --> 00:04:52,500
Who had been sentenced to death and was in the first solitary cell

66
00:04:52,958 --> 00:04:56,583
He was chained to prevent him from escaping

67
00:04:56,916 --> 00:05:00,916
This was the group cell, which was all divided but later dismantled

68
00:05:01,625 --> 00:05:03,875
There was a ventilation opening here

69
00:05:04,375 --> 00:05:11,416
Sometimes they would fire bullets
through the opening to break our spirits

70
00:05:12,750 --> 00:05:14,875
Here, there used to be a door

71
00:05:16,750 --> 00:05:22,916
There was a door here. Sometimes we
stood and saw a faint light in the corridor

72
00:05:22,958 --> 00:05:26,125
Because in the end, we only ever saw the jailers

73
00:05:26,666 --> 00:05:28,291
Everyone here wrote his memories

74
00:05:28,791 --> 00:05:31,625
Then they repainted the prison

75
00:05:32,708 --> 00:05:37,208
But later new prisoners came and wrote new memories again

76
00:05:37,833 --> 00:05:38,833
Very few

77
00:05:39,875 --> 00:05:44,708
Witness: At first, they gave a little...
Interviewer: Read us something that was written on the wall

78
00:05:45,083 --> 00:05:50,083
For example, it says, Do not lose heart or
grieve, for you are superior if you are believers

79
00:05:50,375 --> 00:05:54,750
This was likely written by an ISIS member,
because they often imprisoned their own here

80
00:05:54,750 --> 00:05:56,500
There was much mutual accusation among them

81
00:05:57,000 --> 00:06:02,958
The ISIS prisoner considered himself the victim, and so did the jailer

82
00:06:05,791 --> 00:06:10,000
Interviewer: Were you tortured
during your time in solitary confinement?

83
00:06:10,333 --> 00:06:14,500
Yes, in the first solitary cell where I was imprisoned, I was tortured

84
00:06:15,375 --> 00:06:17,333
This place was designated for <i>shabeh</i> [suspension]

85
00:06:18,250 --> 00:06:21,250
From the solitary cells, we could see
who was suspended and recognize them

86
00:06:21,916 --> 00:06:22,916
I was suspended here

87
00:06:24,291 --> 00:06:27,000
For about 10 hours, more or less

88
00:06:28,500 --> 00:06:32,500
I was suspended here, then they brought a young man from Homs

89
00:06:33,125 --> 00:06:36,041
He was kept hanging for three or four days
until he confessed to what they wanted

90
00:06:36,041 --> 00:06:39,291
Faisal asked them, What do you want from him?

91
00:06:40,125 --> 00:06:41,125
They told him

92
00:06:41,625 --> 00:06:44,708
He had to confess that he was going to Idlib to join the Free Army

93
00:06:44,750 --> 00:06:47,250
He said, As you wish, just to save himself

94
00:06:48,041 --> 00:06:49,375
This solitary cell

95
00:06:50,458 --> 00:06:55,291
When you first go to the investigation
room, the first group cell is right in front

96
00:06:55,291 --> 00:06:58,708
They open the doors. My father
was imprisoned in the first group cell

97
00:06:58,750 --> 00:07:02,250
So he could hear our voices as we were
tortured—me, my brothers, and my cousins

98
00:07:02,291 --> 00:07:05,875
When the interrogator finished torturing us, he opened
my father’s window and said, How are you, are you fine?

99
00:07:05,875 --> 00:07:07,291
Just to break him down

100
00:07:07,666 --> 00:07:14,583
Interviewer: Faraj, you mentioned earlier that there were
disciplinary solitary cells. What was their size approximately?

101
00:07:14,625 --> 00:07:19,208
Exactly, these are the ventilation openings
for the disciplinary solitary cells

102
00:07:19,625 --> 00:07:21,291
Here they are, and there are eight disciplinary cells

103
00:07:22,583 --> 00:07:25,791
The door entrance was here, but they later reopened…

104
00:07:26,583 --> 00:07:30,916
All the partitions together, as if it had now become a storage room

105
00:07:31,208 --> 00:07:34,208
Each cell’s area was no more than half a meter

106
00:07:34,708 --> 00:07:37,708
Sometimes a person had to sleep on one side

107
00:07:37,750 --> 00:07:41,291
Meaning that a slightly overweight person couldn’t sleep on his back

108
00:07:42,041 --> 00:07:43,875
Interviewer: Approximately how many solitary cells were there?

109
00:07:43,916 --> 00:07:49,916
The regular solitary cells were six

110
00:07:50,250 --> 00:07:52,708
As for the disciplinary ones, there were eight

111
00:07:53,125 --> 00:07:57,833
Eight disciplinary cells on one side and five on the other, so a total of 13

112
00:07:57,875 --> 00:07:59,333
Interviewer: How long did you stay in the disciplinary cell?

113
00:07:59,333 --> 00:08:06,291
I stayed in the disciplinary cell from one week
to 10 days, meaning my time there was intermittent

114
00:08:07,458 --> 00:08:11,708
Interviewer: Tell us how you communicated
with each other in the disciplinary cells

115
00:08:12,083 --> 00:08:15,750
When we were in the disciplinary cell, they would
let us go to the bathroom during prayer times

116
00:08:15,750 --> 00:08:18,000
And the bathroom was on this side

117
00:08:18,458 --> 00:08:20,166
We would communicate with the second group cell

118
00:08:21,291 --> 00:08:22,291
The one next to us

119
00:08:22,541 --> 00:08:27,208
Through the long ventilation opening. If you
called out through it, those beside you could hear

120
00:08:27,583 --> 00:08:31,083
So we used to call each other from this side

121
00:08:31,083 --> 00:08:34,000
Once there was a young man named Khaled al-Harbi, who was killed

122
00:08:34,541 --> 00:08:40,500
He used to talk to me. My father and I were in the cell
when the jailer heard us and sent me back to solitary here

123
00:08:41,250 --> 00:08:44,791
So through the ventilation openings we
used to communicate between solitary cells

124
00:08:44,833 --> 00:08:47,750
But in a low voice because the investigation room was very close to us

125
00:08:47,750 --> 00:08:51,583
Interviewer: Which group cell is this? We saw a label written on the wall

126
00:08:52,375 --> 00:08:53,500
Which group cell is this?

127
00:08:53,750 --> 00:08:55,083
This is the second group cell

128
00:08:55,916 --> 00:08:59,708
My father and I were imprisoned
here for a month, then they separated us

129
00:09:00,250 --> 00:09:02,083
Interviewer: Can we see the other group cells?

130
00:09:02,250 --> 00:09:05,208
The other group cells have another door

131
00:09:06,916 --> 00:09:07,916
Of course, this one

132
00:09:09,125 --> 00:09:13,708
This iron door was completely closed, and when it was opened

133
00:09:14,750 --> 00:09:16,041
Cold air would rush in

134
00:09:17,458 --> 00:09:19,000
We’ll talk about that shortly

135
00:09:20,958 --> 00:09:21,958
We enter from here

136
00:09:23,083 --> 00:09:24,541
And here was the first group cell

137
00:09:27,500 --> 00:09:30,291
This is the first group cell, where I was imprisoned twice

138
00:09:32,750 --> 00:09:36,750
The first time I stayed for four days, not counting
this whole period of imprisonment I’m describing

139
00:09:37,000 --> 00:09:39,000
Here were all the prisoners’ memories

140
00:09:39,666 --> 00:09:43,916
I was imprisoned here with someone named Abdul Razzaq al-Barish

141
00:09:44,416 --> 00:09:49,083
I was released, but he wasn’t. He and his brother Faisal were killed

142
00:09:49,416 --> 00:09:50,750
We were imprisoned here together

143
00:09:51,666 --> 00:09:53,916
And here my father and all my brothers were imprisoned

144
00:09:54,958 --> 00:09:57,416
There was an electrical socket on this wall

145
00:09:57,958 --> 00:10:02,500
We used it to communicate with group cell four,
whose door is far from here. We’ll see it shortly

146
00:10:03,000 --> 00:10:07,791
We communicated from here, as there was a power
socket, and through it we could talk to each other

147
00:10:08,208 --> 00:10:12,666
Just by hearing a knock on the
wall, we knew a prisoner wanted to talk

148
00:10:12,708 --> 00:10:15,916
We would immediately come here and
speak to him, and the sound would be clear

149
00:10:15,958 --> 00:10:18,708
Interviewer: What was the most
striking phrase you saw written here in the prison?

150
00:10:23,375 --> 00:10:27,791
As I told you, there was a man named
Abu Madian, who influenced me the most

151
00:10:28,375 --> 00:10:30,875
They erased all his writings in the other group cells

152
00:10:31,250 --> 00:10:33,458
But here he had a small inscription

153
00:10:34,166 --> 00:10:39,291
It was written here, though I don’t know if
it’s still visible. He wrote his son’s name

154
00:10:40,083 --> 00:10:41,083
This is Madian

155
00:10:42,708 --> 00:10:48,291
He used to write on the pillows and mattresses—wherever
you went, you’d find the names Madian and Abu Madian

156
00:10:48,875 --> 00:10:51,791
His real name was Muhammad al-Hateel, but he was known as Abu Madian

157
00:10:53,250 --> 00:10:55,291
He had spent 110 days in prison

158
00:10:56,458 --> 00:10:57,458
And he was killed

159
00:10:59,583 --> 00:11:01,583
He was a calligrapher, may God have mercy on him

160
00:11:05,958 --> 00:11:11,000
Interviewer: Who were the people with you in
the group cell, if you still remember them?

161
00:11:11,291 --> 00:11:15,000
In this group cell, there was Hassan al-Ibrahim imprisoned with me

162
00:11:15,875 --> 00:11:17,208
Hassan Ibrahim al-Sheikh

163
00:11:17,958 --> 00:11:21,958
Walid al-Haji and Mutasim al-Haji

164
00:11:22,500 --> 00:11:24,875
And Muhammad Abdul Fattah al-Oweihi

165
00:11:25,791 --> 00:11:29,958
And Ghanem al-Ibrahim. We were imprisoned together, along with several others whose names I forgot

166
00:11:30,208 --> 00:11:33,416
Witness: But I’ve forgotten their names
Interviewer: Do you have any memories on the prison wall?

167
00:11:33,541 --> 00:11:36,375
I didn’t write anything myself, but
there’s a note from my brother Ibrahim

168
00:11:36,375 --> 00:11:40,375
We were imprisoned together for a while.
That’s his name here—Ibrahim al-Salama

169
00:11:46,416 --> 00:11:48,333
He also has another name written here

170
00:11:49,000 --> 00:11:50,416
And I didn’t write any memory here

171
00:11:52,875 --> 00:11:58,000
Most of my memories were in the solitary cells
because I spent most of my imprisonment there

172
00:11:58,458 --> 00:12:01,208
They painted the walls so no one could recognize

173
00:12:02,291 --> 00:12:04,125
What happened to the prisoners

174
00:12:05,791 --> 00:12:09,208
Now we’ll go to group cell four

175
00:12:09,250 --> 00:12:12,916
Interviewer: During torture, where did it take place?

176
00:12:12,916 --> 00:12:16,125
From where did you hear the screams of those tortured?

177
00:12:16,166 --> 00:12:18,250
From the investigation room. It’s very close

178
00:12:18,250 --> 00:12:22,291
So those in the first group cell, the other cells,
and the solitary ones all heard the torture

179
00:12:22,875 --> 00:12:24,208
This is the investigation room

180
00:12:25,375 --> 00:12:27,375
They used this door to hang the tortured prisoners

181
00:12:28,375 --> 00:12:30,250
Like the other door, and this one too

182
00:12:30,291 --> 00:12:35,208
Sometimes they would hang three people at the same time

183
00:12:35,625 --> 00:12:37,791
You could only hear the groaning of those tortured

184
00:12:38,541 --> 00:12:40,208
Sometimes the beating happened here

185
00:12:40,250 --> 00:12:42,291
Then we’d hear that they were outside the investigation room

186
00:12:42,291 --> 00:12:44,375
They might drag someone out here and start beating him

187
00:12:44,583 --> 00:12:51,000
Interviewer: You and your father
tried to escape using a piece of metal

188
00:12:51,125 --> 00:12:52,125
Yes, of course

189
00:12:52,125 --> 00:12:55,083
Interviewer: From where and which direction did you try to escape?

190
00:12:56,208 --> 00:12:58,958
Over there is group cell four, which is far from here

191
00:12:59,791 --> 00:13:04,666
It’s a bit distant and separate from the
other detention areas and solitary cells

192
00:13:05,875 --> 00:13:07,916
That’s where we were imprisoned in the beginning

193
00:13:08,750 --> 00:13:12,208
So I tried to escape along with the others who were with me

194
00:13:12,541 --> 00:13:16,000
ISIS used to take out one or two prisoners every four or five days

195
00:13:16,041 --> 00:13:18,625
So we kept telling ourselves maybe we’d be next, maybe not

196
00:13:19,416 --> 00:13:20,416
Then we were left alone

197
00:13:21,375 --> 00:13:25,583
Here there was a large group cell, as they had removed the partitions

198
00:13:26,583 --> 00:13:28,416
And this was the entrance door

199
00:13:29,208 --> 00:13:31,583
The prison was entirely underground

200
00:13:32,541 --> 00:13:35,583
And as we see, it had a ventilation opening about half a meter high

201
00:13:36,000 --> 00:13:40,708
Here there is an old external staircase
to the basement, built since its founding

202
00:13:40,958 --> 00:13:45,458
They sealed it off with bricks and cement in this way

203
00:13:46,458 --> 00:13:49,708
We realized there was a staircase
and a door here, but it was blocked

204
00:13:50,375 --> 00:13:57,916
There was an iron rod that one of the former prisoners
is believed to have pulled from the ventilation window

205
00:13:58,958 --> 00:13:59,958
He left it there

206
00:14:00,208 --> 00:14:06,583
We saw the rod and started planning to escape when the escape period began

207
00:14:07,375 --> 00:14:08,750
They moved us to another group cell

208
00:14:09,000 --> 00:14:12,625
That’s when I met my father in the first group cell

209
00:14:13,166 --> 00:14:17,000
I told him that I and the guys with me were thinking of escaping

210
00:14:17,833 --> 00:14:19,541
He asked me, How? Escape is impossible

211
00:14:19,583 --> 00:14:25,750
I said, Yes, there’s a staircase, an outer door,
and an iron rod placed in the ventilation window

212
00:14:26,208 --> 00:14:30,416
There was a young man named Ahmad Sinu and
another named Hamad, and they were listening to us

213
00:14:30,833 --> 00:14:34,791
Time passed, and they separated us, and my father stayed there

214
00:14:35,041 --> 00:14:42,500
Interviewer: Weren’t you afraid that Ahmad
Sinu and the others might be informants?

215
00:14:42,958 --> 00:14:50,416
No, because we had been together for a long time, and
Ahmad Sinu had escaped some time ago from Raqqa Prison

216
00:14:50,958 --> 00:14:53,083
So we already knew him before entering prison

217
00:14:53,916 --> 00:14:55,583
He managed to escape, but they caught him again

218
00:14:55,625 --> 00:14:59,083
He was sentenced to one year in prison
on charges of smuggling a Yazidi woman

219
00:15:00,500 --> 00:15:05,375
When they first entered the group cell, they recognized
it because it was the largest one among all the cells

220
00:15:05,666 --> 00:15:12,208
They found the staircase and saw the
iron rod still in place. No one had moved it

221
00:15:12,833 --> 00:15:14,416
After some time, they began

222
00:15:14,958 --> 00:15:17,208
The jailer ordered them to carry the winter bedding

223
00:15:17,916 --> 00:15:21,291
Since summer had come, they
placed it on this side opposite the door

224
00:15:22,416 --> 00:15:25,791
My father was an old man, unable to dig with them

225
00:15:26,166 --> 00:15:27,875
So he stood by the door and kept watch

226
00:15:28,000 --> 00:15:32,541
While they moved the bedding, they started
digging between the stones of the wall

227
00:15:33,000 --> 00:15:35,333
Each day they dug a little, for a week

228
00:15:36,166 --> 00:15:41,291
When they finally opened the wall,
they waited until the evening prayer began

229
00:15:42,750 --> 00:15:45,208
Once the prayer had started, they escaped from the prison

230
00:15:45,625 --> 00:15:47,541
Interviewer: How many people escaped?

231
00:15:47,541 --> 00:15:51,708
Those who escaped were my father and two young
men, one named Ahmad Sinu and the other Hamad

232
00:15:53,708 --> 00:16:00,000
Interviewer: Can we see the openings
through which you used to communicate?

233
00:16:00,125 --> 00:16:04,500
This is exactly the electricity opening
where there used to be a socket

234
00:16:05,250 --> 00:16:07,041
We communicated with each other through it

235
00:16:07,083 --> 00:16:12,541
We weren’t afraid of the jailers then because they
were far away, and we could sense when they approached

236
00:16:12,541 --> 00:16:15,166
We could talk freely, but those on the other side couldn’t

237
00:16:15,208 --> 00:16:20,583
Interviewer: Did you have a specific time for the jailers’
rounds, or did you have a clock inside the prison?

238
00:16:21,583 --> 00:16:27,000
We would hear the call to prayer and the
Iqama, during the prayer, they would pray

239
00:16:27,375 --> 00:16:30,083
That’s when we took the chance to talk for five minutes or more

240
00:16:30,458 --> 00:16:33,750
Until they finished, because the jailer
would then start his round of inspection

241
00:16:35,000 --> 00:16:41,208
Interviewer: After your father and the
others escaped, you stayed in prison

242
00:16:41,666 --> 00:16:45,708
Interviewer: Tell us about the changes
and movement that happened afterward

243
00:16:45,916 --> 00:16:50,125
The next morning, the prison changed completely

244
00:16:50,583 --> 00:16:55,083
ISIS became confused. We realized something
strange had happened

245
00:16:56,333 --> 00:16:58,875
We knew that a prisoner had managed to escape

246
00:16:59,125 --> 00:17:04,000
They gave us a standard uniform
and took away all our civilian clothes

247
00:17:04,708 --> 00:17:08,208
They installed cameras in all the group cells and solitary cells

248
00:17:09,125 --> 00:17:14,250
They even put up a curtain behind the door

249
00:17:14,833 --> 00:17:17,833
They hung it on their side, not ours

250
00:17:18,166 --> 00:17:22,000
Outside the door, there was a curtain
from the top to the bottom of the door

251
00:17:22,125 --> 00:17:24,833
So we couldn’t see, because they sensed what had happened

252
00:17:25,791 --> 00:17:27,958
Interviewer: What about the jailers who were on duty?

253
00:17:27,958 --> 00:17:32,166
Weren’t they punished or transferred to another prison?

254
00:17:34,875 --> 00:17:38,041
No, I stayed for 15 days or more

255
00:17:38,583 --> 00:17:40,500
I never noticed anything like that

256
00:17:41,666 --> 00:17:43,208
Interviewer: Did their behavior toward you change?

257
00:17:43,625 --> 00:17:50,083
Yes, their behavior changed. They
stopped treating the prisoners with any respect

258
00:17:50,166 --> 00:17:52,666
Before, we could ask them for small
things, and sometimes they would agree

259
00:17:53,041 --> 00:17:56,208
But afterwards, they cut off all communication completely

260
00:17:56,500 --> 00:18:00,833
They started checking the ventilation openings daily

261
00:18:01,041 --> 00:18:04,500
Interviewer: Were you allowed to
go out for fresh air or see sunlight?

262
00:18:04,541 --> 00:18:09,208
No, that was completely forbidden. They
never even thought of allowing it

263
00:18:09,250 --> 00:18:13,041
Sometimes we went out to clean the corridor

264
00:18:13,125 --> 00:18:15,375
But only by order

265
00:18:16,375 --> 00:18:18,208
You could say it was a punishment

266
00:18:19,125 --> 00:18:21,458
Interviewer: Did they give you
ideological lessons in the prison?

267
00:18:21,583 --> 00:18:23,875
Never, no religious or ideological lessons at all

268
00:18:23,916 --> 00:18:26,500
Sometimes we asked for books; they might bring them or not

269
00:18:26,708 --> 00:18:33,208
Interviewer: You mentioned earlier that when you
prayed or recited the Quran aloud, they forbade you

270
00:18:33,208 --> 00:18:34,208
What was the reason?

271
00:18:34,291 --> 00:18:37,458
Because we all knew each other here

272
00:18:38,125 --> 00:18:41,041
Sometimes they told us someone had
confessed to something and had been released

273
00:18:41,250 --> 00:18:44,041
Then we’d hear him reciting the Quran aloud

274
00:18:44,041 --> 00:18:49,208
They realized it, and eventually they banned
reciting the Quran aloud, and even banned prayer

275
00:18:50,416 --> 00:18:55,875
Interviewer: When they took people
for executions and you heard the sounds

276
00:18:56,083 --> 00:19:03,083
Tell us how the process went, and what you felt at that moment

277
00:19:04,041 --> 00:19:10,083
It was psychological destruction. What hurt
me most was for the one being taken to die

278
00:19:10,958 --> 00:19:17,750
He had no idea. As soon as I
heard them carrying the digging tools

279
00:19:18,125 --> 00:19:20,958
I knew they were taking someone to kill him

280
00:19:20,958 --> 00:19:26,291
It could be my turn next, and I could be that
person, not knowing that my time had come

281
00:19:26,833 --> 00:19:31,083
They would tell most of the prisoners being taken

282
00:19:31,750 --> 00:19:36,333
Your behavior is good, stay committed
to religion, try to join us, and so on

283
00:19:36,750 --> 00:19:39,791
So that he wouldn’t think of escaping while being led to execution

284
00:19:40,500 --> 00:19:45,000
Interviewer: Were there cameras
in the solitary cells and group cells?

285
00:19:45,291 --> 00:19:50,416
Before my father and the others
escaped, there were only two cameras

286
00:19:50,833 --> 00:19:53,833
One at the beginning of the corridor and one
at the end; those were the only visible ones

287
00:19:54,166 --> 00:19:57,708
After my father escaped, they placed a
camera in every solitary cell and group cell

288
00:20:03,000 --> 00:20:04,500
Interviewer: When they released you from prison

289
00:20:04,541 --> 00:20:08,541
Did they release you from the same place,
or transfer you somewhere else first?

290
00:20:08,583 --> 00:20:13,083
No, they released me from the same place while
I was blindfolded, after the sunset prayer

291
00:20:14,125 --> 00:20:15,125
And I was out

292
00:20:16,708 --> 00:20:19,416
I was released normally, from the same place I had entered

293
00:20:19,791 --> 00:20:23,000
I left from the car garage, and
they threw me out in the market

294
00:20:24,000 --> 00:20:26,583
One of them asked me, Do you know
where you were imprisoned? I said, No

295
00:20:27,000 --> 00:20:28,750
But he knew that I knew where I had been held

296
00:20:29,166 --> 00:20:30,458
For a reason of his own
